Overall, good. Some dish are pretty good and distint.

Hoona, thank you for helping my elderly mother up the steps and get around the restaurant. You went above and beyond the call of duty. Whoever is in charge of the restaurant should be thankful he works there, thank you!

The happy hour is excellent, the food, service and ambiance are awesome. Will come back, thanks!
Amazing Thai food. Saw things on the menu I've never seen at a Thai restaurant. Really enjoyed the fried chicken curry. Large portions for a decent price which is such a rarity nowadays.

I think that overall the concept of the restaurant is nice and it highlights the diversity of modern Thai food. That being said, I found the flavors to be very restricted. While Thai food is often balanced between salty, sweet, sour, and spicy, the default spice level at this place is mild and they won't let you order it any hotter which makes the food very boring for me (there is also no spice tray with prik nam pla so there is little room to adjust it yourself). I find that this food leans very heavily towards the salty and sweet side which are not my favorites.

I had an extremely unpleasant experience at this restaurant. While taking my order, the waitress raised her voice at me when she failed to understand my question. Instead of communicating in full sentences, she spoke in fragmented words, making it difficult for me to understand her. When I tried to place my order, she continued to shout rudely, aggressively asking if my order was correct. I was baffled as to why I had to endure such behavior and asked her not to raise her voice as it was making it even harder for me to understand. She abruptly stopped taking my order and called over another server. The new server simply asked, "Are you going to order more?" When I expressed my displeasure, she ignored my feelings and continued to press about the order.

Such an experience is truly appalling. It's inappropriate to shout and speak in an unintelligible manner instead of providing proper responses to questions. I feel this establishment desperately needs to invest in staff training for appropriate customer interaction.

I am very disappointed with the customer service at the front desk of Kin Len Thai. I asked the host how long the wait was for a table, but he was very impatient and rude. He told me to go ask the dining customers myself. I have never been treated so poorly at a restaurant before.

In addition to the above, I would also like to add that the host's actions were not only rude and unprofessional, but also potentially dangerous. He was essentially asking me to approach strangers and ask them about their wait time. This could have put me in an uncomfortable or even dangerous situation.

I urge Kin Len Thai to take action to address this issue. The host should be disciplined for his behavior, and the restaurant should implement training programs to ensure that all of its staff members know how to provide excellent customer service.
Front desk waiter is rude and impatient.

Main - Pad Se Ew: Good. The texture was a little more silky than other places so that gets 5 stars. The flavor was a nice balance between sweet and savory. Not enough egg, and the pork pieces felt too chewy / not hot, so I took a star off.

I am in Seattle for a work trip and this place came highly recommended - and it did not disappoint! The interior was super cozy and felt quite authentic, the menu was very fun and inclusive (we had a vegan with us that ate quite well!), and the staff very accommodating.

Waiter was rude with a bad attitude, atmosphere was soo loud I couldn‚Äôt even talk to the person next to me, and then I ordered my food‚Ä¶ it was FULL of red pepper‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs a noodle dish but I couldn‚Äôt even enjoy taste the food- and I‚Äôve been to Thailand and love spicy food.

Overall, we had a good experience here! I highly recommend the battered chicken red curry. It‚Äôs definitely a shareable meal! The Thai papaya salad was fresh and delicious. We also ordered the banana blossom fries, and I thought it was just okay and not something I necessarily recommend. I also ordered the Tamarind Sangria, which was good but could up the tamarind flavor. All in all, I still would recommend eating here!
Very tasty dishes and many vegetarian options

I think I have found the best Thai place in Seattle. Kin Len is such a hidden treasure. The food was ASTOUNDING and truly takes an artistic approach to modern Thai dishes. Highly recommend if you‚Äôre looking for good Thai food.

Great spot for late night thai. This place has happy hour which was at a pretty good price but we came around 7.

I ordered the Battered Chicken with red curry and the durian tiramisu. The chicken was nice and crispy and the curry was warm and creamy 9/10. Looking forward to going back

For its inexpensive price yet amazing food, I‚Äôm definitely coming here again!

I love their presentations and the food was good too. Though I would prefer if they could have options for spice level as I can always order accordingly to my taste.

Super good, inventive thai food and drinks. We went here on a bit of a whim, and it was a great choice.

My experience at Kin Len Thai Night Bites was a mix of highs and lows.

The food was unquestionably a highlight - it was not only delicious but also beautifully presented, adding to the overall dining enjoyment. Moreover, the restaurant offers a diverse range of street food options, making it a great place for culinary exploration.

In terms of service, most of the staff were attentive and pleasant. However, there were some inconsistencies in their friendliness. What stood out negatively was the experience with the host on duty. Upon my arrival, the host appeared to be more focused on chatting and interacting with coworkers rather than welcoming or acknowledging my presence. It took the ringing of the phone at the host station for him to return to his duties and attend to me. Furthermore, when my sister arrived later, she asked him for assistance in locating our table, but his response lacked helpfulness and guidance.

While the food and ambiance were praiseworthy, the service, particularly from the host, fell short of expectations. Considering this, I would give Kin Len Thai Night Bites a rating of 2 out of 5.

I am absolutely appalled by the level of rudeness and disrespect I received from the receptionist at this restaurant. The customer service was by far the worst I have ever experienced. The receptionist consistently ignored us and even went so far as to call us liars, which is completely unacceptable.

When we arrived, I didn't have my full party with me, so I asked if I could join the waitlist. The receptionist gave me an iPad to fill out our information, and the text message indicated that the wait time would be approximately 20 minutes. As soon as she left, a party of 6 walked in, and the receptionist immediately gave them a table. When I reminded him that we were still waiting, he first completely ignored me and walked away. Then when he returned, he rolled his eyes and accused us of lying about the number of people in our party, even though we clearly had four people.

1. Papaya Salad - One of the best we had and pretty close to the one you get in Thailand

5. Rad Na (Crispy wide rice noodles (dine-in only), crispy egg noodles, Chinese broccoli, carrot with pork) - This dish lacked flavor and seasoning and did not taste good or upto the mark. Disappointed.
6. Drinks - Fresh Crack Coconut & Thai Tea Cremosa - Both the drinks were refreshing and tasty. Thai tea comes with whipped cream you can ask them to take it off as well.

Outstanding Thai food in Fremont. My girlfriend and I ordered the betel leaf appetizer, grilled squid, grilled pork jowl, and duck laap. Everything was cooked amazingly, though my only gripe was that the serving of the betel leaf appetizer was a bit too large for the two of us - it was fairly sweet so while it tasted delicious, after about two each it was a lot of sugar for an appetizer. Food is amazing. Drinks are not good ( tried the  leechy and fire cracker). Service was bad!
Really satisfied with the food, nice taste and good price. However the service was terrible, waiter pretend not see us.
awful no service and 30mins wait while there is no customerÔºÅÔºÅ

Food was really good but the wait was insane and we were given a terrible estimate for how long it would take before committing to waiting. They told us 30 min and it took 1.5 hours. Probably would not have waited if they had given us the correct estimate.

This place is great little spot for some zesty Thai food and quick bites. Parking is a little annoying since it‚Äôs Fremont and will most likely be street parking. There might be a wait depending on when you go but it should be easy to get in. The fried chicken wings are bigger than usual wings but very tasty and covered in a sweet but caramelized sauce. The Pad Thais are also a nice option and have a good serving size. Overall the restaurant has a nice bar type vibe and is fun to eat at. The atmosphere feels cozy. Service is great as well. I definitely recommend this place for happy hour and will be back myself.
This is the best Thai food I've had in the Pacific Northwest.

The wait may be long, but it‚Äôs worth it! Tried several items off their menu so far; a great place to go family style and get lots of dishes.

Really amazing Pad Kee Mao and Khao Soi, so generous with the amount of chicken they add! Their drinks are phenomenal (loved the Tamarind Sangria, Mango Mangrove, and Lychee Martini) and the happy hour is awesome!!
The food is really good.
Nice vibe. Good quantity in servings.
Khao soi is delish
Really nice place with cool decor. The food is great as well, their happy hour boat noodles (as well as the other happy hour stuff) is an especially good deal!

Wait was about 50 minutes on a Thursday evening (they don't accept reservations) for a table of three. The menu is online, accessible via a QR code but they have paper menus if you ask (which I did). All of the food items have pictures, which I appreciate. Prices of the dishes ranged from approximately $14-30.
The menu is quite large and it was difficult to narrow down what to order because everything looked so delicious. The three of us shared multiple dishes including Kin Len chicken wings, pad kee mao, Tom yum crispy pork belly fried rice, and battered chicken red curry. The food came out as it was ready so it was great for sharing.we had plenty of food with leftovers.
The space is quite large and the decor has a vintage industrial vibe. I will definitely return to try additional dishes.
Not the Thai food I've been used to, refreshing!
Amazing happy hour and good food overall.  One of my favorites in Seattle :>
The best Thai food!!!! The food is so rich in flavor !! The place has a unique and cool atmosphere! Portions are a good size with left overs !!!
My partner had the battered chicken on the waiter's recommendation and I had the vegan red curry. Both were terrible.

Not the best Thai food.
Many tables .

TL;DR: bought the food, not the service.

The food is so amazing! Highly recommend the beef flank curry. I don‚Äôt know what magic they did with the beef but it got to be the juiciest one I‚Äôve had in Seattle.

HOWEVER, I don‚Äôt know what happened to that one male waiter. Boy was he so impatient! I‚Äôll have to lower the tip if he do it again next time.

The ambiance was nice but the server wasn‚Äôt friendly and the order of which the food came out was off. We sat at a table for 6 even though I asked for 7. We ordered crispy wontons for appetizer and 7 other dishes for each person.

Normally at any restaurant, the kitchen or server would serve the food for the table around the same time. But the server brought out one dish (not the appetizer), 20 minutes went by, brought out a second dish, 15 minutes went by, brought out two more dishes (still no appetizer), 10 minutes, brought out one dish, and another 10 minutes went by then they finally brought out the appetizer but that wasn‚Äôt even the last dish.

The service was bad. The food was ok. Needless to say, I won‚Äôt be going back.
Bad service

Our server Beer was amazing! My meal came out late so we all did a shot of tequila. Great start to a vacation! Everything was amazing and the red curry flank steak is worth the wait! Best red curry ever! Not just the tequila talking ;)
Yummy! Food coming fast! Thai spicy üå∂
The best compliment I can give this place is that I went 3 times in one week and it didn't get old at all. Fantastic food and drinks; definitely try the enoki fritters.

We went out for a date night on Friday to Kin Len on recommendation from a co worker, our experience here made our weekend! We sat at the bar and our bartender Nicole was, efficient, friendly, fast and thoughtful. We tried the fire cracker and the lychee martini and they were delicious. The food was incredible, great portion sizes for the prices and everything came out perfect. The restaurant itself was very clean, orderly and had a happy vibe. This is one of our new favorite spots. So glad we decided to give it a try.
Good environment. Food is delicious and the portion is generous. Will definitely visit again whenever I‚Äôm in Seattle.
The vegan menu is awesome!!! The corn salad with coconut meat will blow your mind. Yum!
Excellent

Spend way too many happy hours here. Probably ordered just about every thing off the happy hour menu and it's all pretty good and appropriately priced. Their full menu has all the pictures so don't forget to check that out.

Food: 8/10

Experience: 8/10

Late review, came here last year, got takeaway due to COVID and it was still some of the best Thai food I have ever had. First time I've had khao soi and I'm hooked. Have ordered it ever since at other restaurants and they don't even come close to the one here. I literally have dreams of their khao soi
Their vegetarian platter has great taste and the fried tofu with chilli oil is to die for! MUST TRY!
Good price
I like the pineapple fried rice and larb duck salad. Also really enjoyed the mango sticky rice. The 2 in one pork rice was pretty good but not great

Love this Thai spot for their amazing foods, unique cocktails, and fun Thai market themed decor. Their Pad Kee Mao is one of my favorites in Seattle though you can't get it as spicy as some other places. The Chinese Eggplant with Rice was also a favorite of our table. This is a great place to bring people visiting Seattle to fill up before a night of going out.

Easy street parking on the same street as the restaurant and short wait times for a table. Friendly and attentive service as well.

The food was good. Main issue was that they locked the doors to the ADA ramp for wheelchairs and strollers. We had to carry our stroller up stairs. They could barely figure out how to unlock the doors when we asked to leave. This could be a fire hazard I hope they have fixed the issue. I raised my concerns with them but they seemed confused how it could be a risk to lock emergency exit doors.

We ordered several dishes and the hot pot everything is the one that really impressed us (although it tasted like vietnamese pho, not Thai flavor). It is mixed with different types of beef and only costs $21. Pad Thai, Papaya salad and mango sticky rice are just normal. Spicy bomb wings were not as expected and too sweet like eating sugar. Staff were too busy and showed impatiently when we asked about changing the spicy level.
Love the food but they need to fix their customer service, slow and rude.

A great Thai food bar with affordable price and authentic flavor!
The shrimp clay pot is pretty delicious with lots of shrimps!
The beef green curry is also pretty good, but it might be better to come with some rice for it.
It comes with fried roti, which is a bit inadequate and too oily in my opinion.

The lychee martini is pretty good with reasonable price in happy hour.
A recommended Thai restaurant in Fremont!

I was here with my friends last week to celebrate my birthday. Love it! The vibe was so fun, and the food is okay. We had 4 people, they automatically add an 18% tip to the bill. Reasonable for a big party.

I decided to take my husband again today to experience their food. The food is still okay, except for the Beef Tongue, extremely tough to chew. There was a guy who asked us how was everything once, but nobody refill our water after that. I understand because they seem busy. But when I gave them a 15% tip, the girl who helped us ask me with a very sarcastic voice: "Is everything okay? Was the food and service okay? Just for you know our standard tip is 18%, but it's okay it's okay!". I work in a hospitality industry too, so I know how important to give a decent tip. But I was so surprised by the way she mocking us for better tip. For me with that kind of service, 15% was reasonable, we didn't complain anything to them, didn't ask them to pay extra attention to us. I'm not comfortable with her forcing attitude. If the standard tip is 18%, they should include that sentence on the menu, or explain it to us before we pay or including into the bill so we aware it. Nope, she let me choose. And the funniest thing is, when we started to leave, she stood right there, just look at us without saying thank you or anything. Come on...

The situation was so awkward that I didn't even want to confront her and end up giving 18%. I know the restaurant's located in an expensive neighborhood, but not every customer is comfortable giving an 18% ~ 20% tip, especially the students, I thought 15% tip for a so-so service was enough, but apparently, it wasn't for her. I'm pretty sure they have lots of customers, so maybe it doesn't important if they lose one. ‚Äç

foods were amazing and the atmosphere was good as well.

This is my first time come to this restaurant, and everything is perfect to me. Except of I went there too late, so the dessert already sold out...
The beef tongue is my favorite!! I have to go back again for the beef tongue!!
I was living in that area, but I never noticed that there is such an amazing thai restaurant! The papaya salad is go to food for me from there as well because it tastes so fresh and delicious! Amazingly good. Good food, various choices, environment is nice. Would love to come again.

One of my go to spots to take people when they come into town. Love the location and layout of this place!

Came here at the end of happy hour and got a lychee martini and tofu pad see ew. Had to wait a while for food, but was WORTH IT. Delicious and cool vibes

My friends and I came during a week night for dinner, and there was no wait. The place was really cute, food was AMAZING, and price was extremely reasonable. I stopped by for their happy hour on a Friday afternoon. I got the chicken red curry from the happy hour menu and it wasn‚Äôt good. It looked as if it was microwaved as part of the stew was hot and part of it cold. The service was ok.
Giving 3 stars because I normally love this place, but a couple nights ago I ordered the spicy bomb wings and they were super tough, dry, and leathery. They were terrible!

The worst service ever. The waiter basically humiliate me in front of my friends for me trying to hand over my card. Very interesting Thai food, not your basic neighborhood Thai menu. Eclectic mix of new/different foods from all regions of Thailand. They even have an entire vegan/vegetarian menu! Highly recommend eating here, I‚Äôll keep coming back until I try everything on the menu!
Wish I could give 6 stars

Food was good, service was slow.  Drinks,  appetizers,  entrees all came at once after a long wait even though they were ordered separately.  I suspect like many restaurants,  they have post covid staffing issues

Open 11:30 walk-in 11:40 no one in front desk 11:50 server show up and let's us know we still have to wait 30-40 mins before they ready to cook...
The food here is very good. The menu is pretty limited though.

Probably the best Thai food I‚Äôve ever had. Got the crispy pork belly with broccoli and was superb. The curry dishes were out of this world too and my buddy Eopia got a fried chicken dish that was incredible. Great water for the table too

We had "crispy wrappers", "papaya salad", "boat noodle beef", "crispy mussels omlet", "kin len wing with sticky rice" with a glass of beer and cocktail for about $56 with tips.
Foods are great, friendly service and cute cozy spacious indoor seating.
We were hungry and we thought happy hour plates may small but their happy hour menu have good portions.
We couldn't finish them. We took left overs home.
One of the best late night vegan places in the Fremont bridge area.  Amazing barter and the quality of the food is terrific.
Best Thai food in Seattle, by far. I've yet to find a dish I'm not totally obsessed with. Every plate is so flavorful and nourishing...and it's vegan friendly! üòä
Beef Hot Pot is sooooo goodÔºÅmeat is so tender, soup is just so perfect, portion size is huge. I will come back definitely and try other food

Ordered some superb takeout from Kin Len tonight. Ordered our old standbys of pad kee mao with pork and tofu pad thai, but with the addition of the crispy pork belly fried rice. Ok food with poor service.

Arrived around 6pm on a weekday, and wait time was one hour. You had to even wait at least 5 mins before you got added to the waitlist cuz there is no staff showing up at the reception. When we came back an hour later to get seated, the staff at reception would rather chatting with another staff than serving or greeting us. Seriously?

Waited another 15 mins to get a staff stop by our table and take our order. The staff only took the order and didn‚Äôt bring us any serving plates or napkins. Is this a self serve restaurant? But why did it charge percentage based tips using the after tax expense?! What a joke. Glad we sit next to the utensil cart where we can grab plates, forks, and spoons by ourselves, which shouldn‚Äôt be like that.

The hot pot beef tasted good upon the first bite, but you might find it too sweet. I don‚Äôt know if there is any MSG in it cuz this dish made me feel uncomfortable and thirsty all night. I had to keep drinking water after visiting Kin Len.

The papaya salad was good but way too spicy. We picked medium spicy but it‚Äôs actually extra spicy, and my partner who can‚Äôt handle spicy food had hard time finishing it. I understand it‚Äôs for the sake of authenticity, but I‚Äôd appreciate it if the waiter can inform us what to expect.

I do want to have peanuts in my papaya salad, but the waiter accidentally took it as ‚Äòno peanuts‚Äô. Fine, I blame the extremely loud noises inside this place. You had to shout to your party to get heard.

They would hand you the portable card reader to select percentage based tips, and that is all based on after tax prices. Sneaky huh? You can choose the custom one to type in tips you actually you want to give them.

Wow. Delicious. This place is the bomb. I've walked by its windows for months now and just yesterday made it a point to grab dinner and drinks.

My friend and I both got cocktails (which were divine - the Green Tea Gin and Tonic is lovely) and a few plates to share. I highly recommend the rice dumplings and khao soi. I legitimately had dreams about the khao soi. Everything was so flavorful, fresh and with a depth of spice that I've never experienced outside of Thailand. Can't wait to go back!

I have eaten at Kin Len a few times. Today, I ordered a crispy papaya salad and a red curry with chicken. The papaya salad was very good, even 30 minutes after I had picked it up. The curry was tasty too, but she forgot to include the rice, so I had to cook some rice at home myself and then re-heat the curry. 3 stars is their "extra spicy", which I specified for the curry, but it was not very spicy. I do recommend a 4-star level option so that the customers can be sure it's spicy when so desired. In general, the food at Kin Len is on the better side compared to many other Thai restaurants in Seattle. However, none of the Thai restaurants around here manage to actually prepare a curry dish that genuinely tastes authentically Thai. Too much sugar, too much cream, too little variety of vegetables especially, the latter being an important part of authentic Thai curries. It just doesn't taste as good as you find it in most run-of-the-mill street-side restaurants in Thailand. It is possible to find authentic Thai food outside Thailand, for example at restaurant Sch√∂nscharf in Vienna, Austria. But not here.

No customer's  service at all! They just say it will be ready a few minutes and will spend an other 20 minutes minimum. I will go this restaurant twice a week I don't recommend to go if you don't have time especially. They don't care about your time.

AMAZING. If you‚Äôre looking for a super cute, super delicious, and budget friendly stop in Seattle this is the place. The portion sizes are HUGE if you aren‚Äôt a heavy eater, sharing is optimal! One more thing I found out after I picked up the food and went back home, I ordered 5 dishes, one of them was missing, which is a beef pad Thai. Then I tried to call them to ask, no one replied the phone call for the whole night. I was so so so disappointed!

I have been wanting to try this place out for awhile and so glad I did! When you first walk in the menu is right there so you can order what you want right away and it‚Äôs all touch less!

This place is amazingly delicious!
So good!! Probably the best Thai I‚Äôve had in Seattle. Can‚Äôt recommend it enough.

This is the new IT place for Seattle. The unconventional order-before-you're-seated method combined with amazing cocktails and divinely unique dishes is a breath of fresh air for the city's *tired* Thai food scene.

The dining experience itself from start to finish requires a flexible and open mind- think of yourself as a tourist in another country and go with the flow!

Furthermore the pricing: four LARGE high quality (packed with complex levels of FLAVOR) dishes and two specialty drinks for under $80 is unheard of in Seattle. Take note, especially for date night.

My favorite part, besides the flow of ordering before being seated, was the interior design and ambiance. If Seattle wants to compete with restaurants in cities such as New York and Los Angeles they should take a page from this Fremont gem. I can't wait to bring others here.

Service was also great, don't expect people to wait on you hand and foot and you'll love it.

Visited during the soft opening and it‚Äôs super legit. I‚Äôve visited Thailand multiple times - and their street food is one of the things I love most. WHERE DO I FRICKEN START!!!!
(Read only if you love good Thai food!)
Have you ever teared up from finding the food you longed for all your life. For me it's been over a year. I moved up here from California and have only a few food requirements. Good, delicious, savory Thai food. Authentic Japanese food...including ramen, and finally a good chili dog.
I found the ramen and chili dog but really, really good Thai food eluded me. What eluded me even more was some good traditional Thai Boat Noodles.  This place has it !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
When the waiter first served it in front of me I was really reluctant because most Thai restaurants in Washington don't have it or they make a not-so-authentic tasting version that is also not-so-tasty.
Kin Len makes the traditional spicy insane delicious savory Boat Noodles!!!!
I'm gonna try and make it a point to go every few weeks so I can have this!
Also the rest of the dishes and drinks were delicious as well. The steamed bread desert was so simple and good we ended up ordering two of them. I can't remember all of the names of the dishes we ordered since my wife and our friends ordered most of it (they're all Thai) but the fried chicken, dumplings, the veggie spicy salad thing, curry, grilled octopus, and, of course, the Boat Noodles-My friend had it also, neither one of us shared it with our wives or friends. Don't get me wrong, everything was delicious here but I have a special affection for Boat Noodles(and Japanese Ramen).
They have some pictures on the menu which I hope they add more. The entrance is a bit tricky as, since the restaurant is located on the corner, you would think the entrance is right where you think it would be, it's actually 3 doors down. Not a big deal. Just a little odd.
I believe the owners are the same as Isarn Thai Soul Kitchen in Lynnwood and Kirkland. Also an awesomely delicious place!...and they have mango sticky rice. This is my all time favorite dessert. The menu is different from those restaurants which also causes so much conflict within me. Do I go to Isarn and have some delicious thai food and end it with my favorite mango sticky rice?....or do I go to Kin Len and have that awesome "happiness in a bowl" of Boat Noodles and finish it off with the steamed bread dessert????

P.S. sorry for the terrible pic of the Boat Noodles. I was too busy chowing down on it when I realized I needed evidence of this miracle. :)

I'm Thai and the authenticity makes me home without getting a ticket.
We had Mee Kati, Crispy Rice Salad and Miang Lemongrass.

Mee Kati is a sweet and spicy curry on stir-fried thin noodle. It is a great pair with something gingery/limey like Crispy Rice Salad. Crispy Rice Salad here will not be as sweet as other places but I like that a lot. Because many Thai food place sweetens food to make it easier to eat but I think they tried to keep the authenticity level so they choose to do it this way.

Miang Lemongrass is a rare dish (for me at least) to find it here in US. It's like a sweet/sour herbal salad wrapped in herbal leave (Miang). It is so flavorful and fresh. The smell of grounded baked coconut is subtle yet strong enough to add some mild taste to it.

Chrysanthemum tea taste like the one I had in Thailand. It's a Chinese herbal tea.

All in all, really like it. The authenticity of the place is great. They open it as a restaurant/bar so it's opened pretty late.

Noticed "new" restaurant earlier in the day, and decided to stop for dinner on the way home. There were a fair numbers of cars there, for 5pm on a Sunday night. Had no idea what we were walking in to. Once inside, we determined it was Brazilian. The decor is simple, a cross between a cafeteria and cafe in 2 very large rooms, with wooden tables and chairs and a few booths along outside walls. There seemed to be a little confusion about where to seat us, in hindsight, I think they were trying to determine whose section had a server who spoke English well.  I asked for a booth and was accommodated easily. This is an Authentic Brazilian Restaurant. I have been to Brazilian Tapas before, but this is more of a family atmosphere. We got menus which were quite comprehensive, albeit written in Portuguese. Our server came and asked if we needed English menus, and grabbed some for us. üòÇ He explained the menu and we ordered an appetizer and a half serving combo from the steak section. There was more than enough to feed 3 of us and we took home 3 containers with leftovers. My favorites were cheesy chicken strips and the coconut pie w ice cream. The fact we were able to agree and order 2 items that "stuffed" the 3 of us is Extremely Impressive, as we all have very different preferences for our food. It turned out to be a fun adventure and the food was great. The owner/manager even checked in w us at the end of the meal, concerned about a language barrier for us. We had no problem. Highly recommend you check it out. We will go again. Photos of food when it was first delivered, needed 2 shots to fit it all in!

I dined here this weekend.and had an overall enjoyable experience, though there were a few areas that could use improvement.

Upon arrival, we were greeted by the hostess. However, her communication regarding seating was somewhat unclear. We were told our table would be ready shortly, but there was confusion about up charge on seating due to love entertainment . A more straightforward approach or clear instructions on where to wait would have been appreciated.

Once seated, we immediately noticed the noise level. The restaurant was bustling, and while it‚Äôs great to see a lively atmosphere, the noise was overwhelming at times. It was difficult to hold a conversation without raising our voices. Better acoustics or sound dampening measures would greatly enhance the dining experience.

The service was friendly and attentive, with our waiter checking in on us regularly. However, the pace of service was slow. It took a considerable amount of time for our orders to arrive, and even simple requests like water refills were delayed. While the staff was courteous and apologetic, quicker service would improve the overall dining experience.

Despite these issues, the food was good. and well worth the wait. With a few adjustments to communication, noise control, and service speed, this place could elevate its dining experience to match the quality of competitors in the area.

First, the atmosphere. The space is open, with huge vaulted ceilings and a gorgeous view of the reservoir. We came for lunch during a  snow storm in April and it was an experience to sit by the huge windows overlooking the lake and enjoy the view. I can imagine an evening anniversary or date night would be unbelievably special with the lights coming off the lake.

The service was incredible. Patricia, our server, was unbelievably knowledgeable and generous with her time. She walked us through the HUGE, unique menu and gave suggestions for sides that would match the experience we were hoping to have. The food came out fast, hot, and she explained everything that she delivered with excitement and knowledge.

Of note, the menu is in fact huge. And unique: you order family style, for either 2-4 guests, or you can order individual entrees. I loved how this allowed my family to try multiple of the beautiful unique entrees while also encouraging a super social and interactive experience. That being said if you want your own entree, they have individual options so that is no big deal.

We had the pork belly roll - holy sh*t. I‚Äôve eaten so much pork belly in my life, and this is the best and most unique pork belly I‚Äôve ever had. So crunchy on the outside and so soft and juicy on the inside. It‚Äôs sold as a full appetizer with yuca fries or individually as a side as one roll. An experience NOT to miss.

In the same vein, the dried beef and cheese empanadas are unparalleled. I can‚Äôt even think of enough words to describe how incredible they were. My husband and I ate in silence lol

We then shared the top sirloin (!!!!!!!!!!) and the shrimp au gratin. I can‚Äôt tell you how long it‚Äôs been since I‚Äôve had a steak cooked correctly. This mid rare masterpiece was so juicy, it literally melted away in my mouth. I dipped it in the cheese from the shrimp au gratin and it was exceptional.

Our favorite sides were the yuca fries and the pico, which was fresh and perfect.

As we were leaving, the manager Hugo came over to ask about our experience. It was a very special touch that made the afternoon that much better. It was clear that he was not only passionate about Brazilian food, but proud of what Manolo does to provide such a high quality and authentic experience. It‚Äôs easy to want to support such special people.

As local to Framingham, we are thrilled that such a special restaurant is within a few minutes drive from our home. We can‚Äôt wait to eat through the menu this spring and summer.
